### EventStore Implementation

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReadWriteLock;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantReadWriteLock;

public class EventStore {

    public static class Event {
        private final long id;          // R1: 64-bit signed integer
        private final long timestamp;   // 64-bit signed timestamp
        private final byte[] payload;

        public Event(long id, long timestamp, byte[] payload) {
            this.id = id;
            this.timestamp = timestamp;
            this.payload = payload;
        }

        public long getId() { return id; }
        public long getTimestamp() { return timestamp; }
        public byte[] getPayload() { return payload; }
    }

    // Thread-safety locks
    private final ReadWriteLock lock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();

    // R3: Set to keep track of processed IDs to silently reject duplicates
    private final Set<Long> registeredIds = new HashSet<>();

    // R2 & R4: TreeMap dynamically sorts events by timestamp, handling out-of-order arrival
    // and allowing range scans regardless of the physical ingestion order or system clock state.
    private final TreeMap<Long, List<Event>> index = new TreeMap<>();

    /**
     * Inserts an event into the store.
     * Silently ignores the write if the event ID has already been processed.
     */
    public void insert(Event event) {
        if (event == null) return;

        lock.writeLock().lock();
        try {
            // R3: Silently reject duplicate IDs
            if (registeredIds.contains(event.getId())) {
                return; 
            }

            // Mark ID as registered
            registeredIds.add(event.getId());

            // R2: Insert event. TreeMap handles out-of-order timestamps naturally.
            index.computeIfAbsent(event.getTimestamp(), k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(event);
        } finally {
            lock.writeLock().unlock();
        }
    }

    /**
     * Queries all events whose timestamp falls in the [start, end] range (inclusive).
     */
    public List<Event> queryRange(long start, long end) {
        lock.readLock().lock();
        try {
            List<Event> matchedEvents = new ArrayList<>();

            // Extract the inclusive sub-range view [start, end]
            NavigableMap<Long, List<Event>> subMap = index.subMap(start, true, end, true);

            for (List<Event> events : subMap.values()) {
                matchedEvents.addAll(events);
            }

            return matchedEvents;
        } finally {
            lock.readLock().unlock();
        }
    }
}
```

### How the rules are preserved:
*   **(R1) Signed 64-bit IDs**: The `id` is represented as a Java `long`, supporting full negative and positive ranges ($[-2^{63}, 2^{63}-1]$).
*   **(R2) Out-of-order arrival**: Events are indexed in a `TreeMap`. No matter the ingestion order, events are instantly sorted by their logical `timestamp` key.
*   **(R3) Silent duplicate rejection**: The `registeredIds` set filters duplicates. If an ID has been seen, `insert` returns immediately without throwing errors or updating the indexes.
*   **(R4) Non-monotonic system clock**: The store depends solely on the timestamps explicitly defined inside the incoming `Event` payloads. No real-time system clock comparisons are made during ingestion.

To support event subscriptions, we will introduce a registration mechanism. Callers can subscribe by providing a callback (using Java's standard `Consumer<Event>`). 

To ensure high performance and prevent deadlocks, subscribers are notified **synchronously but outside of the core database write lock**. This ensures that slow or poorly written subscribers cannot block other concurrent writes or cause locking deadlocks.

