                this.index.computeIfAbsent(timestamp, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(event);
            }
        } finally {
            lock.writeLock().unlock();
        }
    }

    /**
     * Safely translates numeric values from various JSON parsers to JVM 64-bit signed longs.
     */
    private static long toLong(Object value) {
        if (value instanceof Number) {
            return ((Number) value).longValue();
        } else if (value instanceof String) {
            return Long.parseLong((String) value);
        }
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unsupported type for 64-bit integer conversion: " + value.getClass());
    }
}
```

***

### Summary of Agreed Invariants & Features (In Order of Introduction)

1. **(Invariant R1) 64-bit Signed IDs**: Event identifiers are strict 64-bit signed integers (`long`), and negative values are fully legal.
2. **(Invariant R2) Out-of-Order Support**: Events are permitted to arrive out of chronological order. The storage mechanism must dynamically arrange them correctly by timestamp.
3. **(Invariant R3) Silent Duplicate Rejection**: Multiple events with the same ID cannot be stored. Additional arrivals sharing an existing ID are discarded silently without throwing runtime exceptions.
4. **(Invariant R4) Non-Monotonic System Clock**: No logical operations assume a forward-moving system clock. Time is evaluated strictly based on the stored numerical value inside the Event's `timestamp` payload.
5. **(Feature 1) Range Queries**: The store supports querying all accepted events whose logical timestamp falls into a given `[start, end]` (inclusive) numerical range.
6. **(Feature 2) Live Notifications (Subscriptions)**: Callers can register callbacks (subscribers) to be dynamically notified of newly accepted events. Notifications are triggered synchronously only for non-duplicate, non-tombstoned events, and occur outside the database write lock.
7. **(Feature 3) Snapshot & Reload**: The database state (including active events, timestamps, and metadata indexes) can be exported into a JSON-serializable Map/Dict—representing binary payloads as Base64 strings—and completely restored back into memory.
8. **(Feature 4) Tombstoning (Permanent Bans)**: Callers can delete an event ID. Doing so purges it from the active database and places its ID into a permanent blacklist. The blacklisted ID can **never** be accepted again, even if the corresponding event is re-submitted later due to out-of-order network arrival.
